elvetica, sans-serif; COLOR: #000; FONT-SIZE: 10pt">Namaste friends,<WBR>&n=
bsp;<WBR>Bhakti yoga or the path of surrender and devotion is indeed more s=
uitable in this age. I did not mean to say otherwise.<WBR> <WBR>But ju=
st having an ishta devata is not enough to be "protected" from deep and tro=
ublesome instabilities when one's body-mind complex goes through a big tran=
sformation. Not every aspiring devotee becomes a Prahlada - some become Rav=
anas. After all, out of the two examples Leelaji gave below for "psychologi=
cal disorder", the second lady "did much sadhana of Srirama". Even those wh=
o think of a deity and pray to him/her can end up with hallucinations, ment=
al and spiritual disorders, wrong (colored by one's conditioning and desire=
s!) interpretation of internal/external experiences and even madness.<WBR>&=
nbsp;<WBR>True surrender/devotion to ishta devata will definitely protect o=
ne, but
 cultivating it is as difficult as cultivating detachment through w=
isdom! In fact, true surrender and detachment are almost the same.<WBR>&nbs=
p;<WBR>This is why I said that *lightness of conditioning* is the most impo=
rtant thing. One with dense conditioning will find SOME way to fail even if=
 a great guru or god are ready to help.<WBR> <WBR>*   &=
nbsp;    *        *<WBR>&=
nbsp;<WBR>Now, the question is: How do we reduce our conditioning? Unfortun=
ately, there is no single magic bullet. Thinking of a god, mantras, bhajans=
, japam, homam etc can help, but they need to be augmented by regular intro=
spection and self-improvement.<WBR> <WBR>Taking mind away from its cur=
rent pre-occupations (e.g. "I am smart", "I am doing good sadhana", "I am m=
ad at X", "I did not get what I deserve in Y", "I am better than X", "I mus=
t have Y at any cost" etc etc) is key to eventually overcoming conditioning=
,
 for these thoughts keep *reinforcing* the conditioning!<WBR> <WBR>T=
o reduce the regular pre-occupations of mind, different imagery/visualizati=
on may work better for some people.<WBR> <WBR>One approach is to conte=
mplate god whenever possible, in the middle of any activity. You can imagin=
e a being in your mind, either as an ideal/able person or as a principle/id=
eal/ability that exists in many beings, that is so perfect and fascinating =
for the mind to contemplate that it does not care about other objects aroun=
d that are making shadripus and ashtapashas work on the mind. Whenever mind=
 is about to entertain its regular debilitating pre-occupations, one can tr=
y to contemplate god instead.<WBR> <WBR>Mind is a wild animal. As Pi s=
ays in the movie "Life of Pi" about the tiger on the boat, wild animals can=
't be transformed or domesticated, but they can be trained into some habits=
!<WBR> <WBR>Whenever one is enjoying a sensual pleasure, if one
 think=
s "the omnipresent God is enjoying this thru this instrument" and starts co=
ntemplating the qualities of that god instead of thinking too much about li=
mited sense objects, one is better placed to reduce the damage done by shad=
ripus. Whenever one is angry at someone for what they did, if one thinks "t=
he omnipresent God is giving me the fruits of my karmas thru that instrumen=
t" and starts contemplating the qualities of that god instead of being angr=
y at someone, one is better placed to reduce the damage done by shadripus. =
And so on.<WBR> <WBR>In the beginning, even contemplation of god becom=
es laced with ego. Every now and then, the activity ends up becoming about =
oneself rather than about god ("*I* am doing this nice bhajan", "*I* am doi=
ng this nice homam", "I think *I* am making progress through this"). With e=
ffort and perseverance, one can avoid making it about oneself and keep it c=
entered on the supreme power that runs the show. Just as it
 takes a long t=
ime to train a wild animal, it takes a long time to train mind!<WBR> <=
WBR>Try to develop devotion and surrender. Based on all that you read and h=
eard, develop of a concept/principle of god that is so superb and fascinart=
ing. Visualize/contemplate that concept as frequently as possible, especial=
ly when meditating. When mind veers off into other things, gently steer it =
back. Don't spend too much time dissecting what mind is doing and why. Just=
 put it back gently into contemplating god. Try to make it about god rather=
 than about yourself.<WBR> <WBR>The main drawback of the sadhana of mo=
st people is that they make it about themselves at some level or the other.=
 Though that is unavoidable, try to break free from it.<WBR> <WBR>*&nb=
sp;       *     &nbs=
p;  *<WBR> <WBR>Finally, one can try to overcome the limited sens=
e of self and engage in selfless actions that benefit
 a larger set of peop=
le than oneself. What stops us from truly loving god is our deep and sub-co=
nscious love for *ourselves* (i.e. our *limited* notion of self that drives=
 the current body-mind complex). One way to overcome that is to selflessly =
love others. After all, other people around us are as much replicas of god =
as we are. If we cannot empathize with them, love them and give them uncond=
itionally, how can we ever hope to transcend the limited sense of Self and =
truly love omnipresent God?<WBR> <WBR>
